04766nam a22006495i 9781503603530DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20202017cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815036035307 a10.1515/97815036035302doi  a(DE-B1597)563639  a(OCoLC)1178769508  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aLAW0130002bisacsh04a324.6/209732231 aRhodes, Jesse H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBallot Blocked :bThe Political Erosion of the Voting Rights Act /cJesse H. Rhodes. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2017  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStanford Studies in Law and Politics00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Explaining the Puzzling Evolution of the Voting Rights Act -- t1. Liberal Ascendance and Enactment of the Voting Rights Act of 1965 -- t2. Conservative Backlash and Partisan Struggle over Voting Rights, 1968-1980 -- t3. The Growing Struggle over Voting Rights in the 1980s and 1990s -- t4. Voting Rights Politics in an Era of Conservative Ascendance, 2001-2013 -- t5. Voting Rights Politics in the Age of Obama, 2009-2016 -- tConclusion. Partisan Interests, Institutional Conflict, and the Future of the Voting Rights Struggle -- tNotes -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aVoting rights are a perennial topic in American politics. Recent elections and the Supreme Court's decision in Shelby County v. Holder, which struck down key enforcement provisions in the Voting Rights Act (VRA), have only placed further emphasis on the debate over voter disenfranchaisement. Over the past five decades, both Democrats and Republicans in Congress have consistently voted to expand the protections offered to vulnerable voters by the Voting Rights Act. And yet, the administration of the VRA has become more fragmented and judicial interpretation of its terms has become much less generous. Why have Republicans consistently adopted administrative and judicial decisions that undermine legislation they repeatedly endorse? Ballot Blocked shows how the divergent trajectories of legislation, administration, and judicial interpretation in voting rights policymaking derive largely from efforts by conservative politicians to narrow the scope of federal enforcement while at the same time preserving their public reputations as supporters of racial equality and minority voting rights. Jesse H. Rhodes argues that conservatives adopt a paradoxical strategy in which they acquiesce to expansive voting rights protections in Congress (where decisions are visible and easily traceable) while simultaneously narrowing the scope of federal enforcement via administrative and judicial maneuvers (which are less visible and harder to trace). Over time, the repeated execution of this strategy has enabled a conservative Supreme Court to exercise preponderant influence over the scope of federal enforcement.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aMinoritiesxSuffragezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMinoritiesxSuffragezUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aSuffragezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aSuffragezUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 4aAmerican Political Development. 4aAmerican Presidency. 4aCivil Rights. 4aHistorical Institutionalism. 4aInterest Groups and Social Movements. 4aLaw and Politics. 4aLaw and Society. 4aPolitical Science. 4aSupreme Court. 4aVoting Rights. 7aLAW / Civil Rights.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311070369640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360353040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503603530423Coveruhttps